channel.title: Power supply won't fit in the case
channel.description: Well, my computer runs of a minuscule 220W power supply unit, which is no where near enough to support pretty much any GPU and I was going to get a low wattage card, but I was going to upgrade to a 400w power supply or so, but none of them will fit in my slim case. I really don't want to buy a new case, but I will if I have too. How bad is it to have the power supply handing out of the case? I know that it can collect a lot of dust, which is no good.

item.title: Power supply won't fit in the case
item.dc:creator: @lawl lawl
item.description:
@lawl wrote:

@MITB: I have two cases in which I bought a $30 case+psu combo. One in my pc, one in my dad’s. Worked fine for about 4 years in mine, but for the last 3 years it would make engine-like sounds when I’d boot my pc. Replaced it with a corsair hx650 a few months ago and the small details really make it so much better. Had the power go out for a second once during a thunderstorm and my pc didn’t turn off, I was pretty impressed. It’s also a lot more energy efficient (80 plus, etc.) than a cheap one. As for my dads pc, after about 3 years it randomly died. Thankfully it didn’t take out anything else with it.

So imo, a good psu is a good investment. One good psu would probably last as long as 2-3 cheap psus, so it seems worth it to me.

Also the $20 cases are the shittiest shits on the planet. Bought a nice cooler master case and it was so much more fun to build with. Better airflow, easier to carry, sturdier design, looks nicer…

Read full topic

[/quote]

Haha, no it’s just made out of thinner-than-you’d-like metal and may have a dent in it due to shipping or something. But generally, if it is dented, newegg will just refund you for it and you get to keep it. I’ve been using one for 5+ years now.

As to where you find one, newegg.com:

Looks like they don’t have any really good deals today, cheapest one I see is $30 with $8 shipping…
